Today, I explored an important concept in mathematics and programming: Prime Numbers!





ğŸ¤” What is a Prime Number?

A prime number is a natural number greater than 1 that has only two factors: 1 and itself.





ğŸ“Œ Examples:

 âœ” 2 â†’ âœ… (Prime)

 âœ” 3 â†’ âœ… (Prime)

 âœ” 5 â†’ âœ… (Prime)

 âŒ 4 â†’ âŒ (Not Prime, since 4 = 2 Ã— 2)

 âŒ 6 â†’ âŒ (Not Prime, since 6 = 2 Ã— 3)





ğŸ› ï¸ JavaScript Code to Check for Prime Number

function isPrime(n) {

    if (n < 2) {

        return false;  // Prime numbers start from 2

    }

    for (let i = 2; i < n; i++) {

        if (n % i === 0) {  // If n is divisible by any number other than 1 and itself, it's not prime

            return false;

        }

    }

    return true;

}

console.log(isPrime(5));  // Output: true

console.log(isPrime(4));  // Output: false





â³ Understanding Time Complexity

ğŸ”µ For each number n, we check all numbers from 2 to n-1

If n = 10, we check 2, 3, 4, ..., 9

If n = 100, we check 2, 3, 4, ..., 99

 ğŸ“Œ Since we loop through n numbers, the time complexity is O(n) (Linear Time Complexity).

ğŸ”¹ This is not the most efficient way!

ğŸ”¹ We can optimize it to O(âˆšn) by checking up to âˆšn instead of n-1 (More on that later ğŸ˜‰).





